Lip filler treatment with an experienced patient looking to get her yearly top up for big lips.

The technique performed in the demonstration is linear threading, which I find provides the most comfort for patients.

The lip filler product used was Intraline, however note that this is a primarily UK based project. In Australia I personally use Juvederm and Restylane.

If you have any questions, feel free to leave a comment below.
You can view the video where I demonstrate the treatment or arrange to drop by my clinic at drnora.com

Note: The photos were taken with the patient's consent. The lighting conditions and patient's pose in the before and after photos were taken in as close as possible conditions. The only photo alterations made were to crop and overlay the images for the morph animation. There is a demonstration video available at drnora.com

I promised follow up on the Charles procedure and here it is! If you didn't see the previous posts on this case, go back and check them out!
.
.
The Charles procedure was a procedure described for recalcitrant lymphedema. It is rarely done anymore because there are much better treatments for lymphedema and it's almost a procedure of historical interest... but still has its role in limb salvage. .
.
The procedure itself is simple- debulk all dead skin and subcutaneous tissue to the level of fascia. No muscle is taken. The limb is allowed to granulate for a bit and then split thickness sling grafted circumferentially. .
.
This limb was salvaged rather than amputated at the patient's wishes. She had not neurologic or vascular injury. This will give her a reliable leg to walk on- she has an open hip dislocation treated with a girdlestone and 3b open pilon on the other side... so this side is actually her better leg!
.
.
.

So I had to have stitches... what now? 😒

I'll be honest, I have never had stitches personally, at least not in an emergency setting. But... I DO deal with them on the regular, in the Emergency Department. 💁🏻 Stitches are used to close a wound that will be less likely to heal well on its own. Many small scrapes and cuts can close over time, but the deeper and more gaping the laceration, the more likelihood it will need some help with stitches! 
Some sutures are absorbable and others dissolve. The choice of which suture to use is largely made by the provider, but sometimes involves the patient. Depending on the location of injury, sutures may need to be left in for 5-14 days, sometimes longer when it's a post operative wound (like this one pictured in photo).
Some wounds require multi-layer closure, and closure using various techniques with different suture types. 
Many people worry about having to have their hair shaved- we don't do that typically in an ER setting. It is done in an operative setting to maintain sterility at the time of procedure (as seen in photo). The aftercare of sutures and wounds is important, and you should always ask your doctor what their recommendations involve. Most wounds that I repair, can be washed gently after 24 hours, using gentle cleanser and lightly patting to dry. It's important not to soak wounds with stitches, and decreasing sun exposure will greatly help with scarring! 
You can thank my boyfriend the firefighter for the photo. Turns out falling from a roof on a building fire can lead to a ruptured ligament in the wrist requiring operative repair. We call this the "monster hand". 👹😳 Keep in mind this post is for education only and does not take the place of your personal doctor's recommendations 😉

POSE Weight loss 
The POSE procedure reduces the size of your stomach without making a single incision into the body by utilizing special tools that access the stomach through the mouth and esophagus. Not only does the procedure not require incisions to reduce the size of the stomach, but it is considered much safer than other surgical options. There has been virtually no complications to date and most patients are able to go back to work within a couple of days. POSE does not require cutting like gastric bypass and the gastric sleeve or a medical implant like the LAP-BAND or REALIZE Band, yet similar results have been achieved.
